TY  - JOUR
T1  - Private Equity as an Intermediary in the Market for Corporate Assets
AU  - Nary, Paul
AU  - Kaul, Aseem
Y1  - 2021/06/08
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2023/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2020.0168
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2020.0168
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 719
EP  - 748
VL  - 48
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examine the role of non-venture private equity (PE) firms as intermediaries in the market for corporate assets. We argue that, in order to create and capture value by acquiring established businesses and selling them to corporate buyers, PE firms must possess at least one of three potential advantages: (a) they must be able to identify businesses that are currently undervalued (valuation advantage), (b) they must be able to enhance the intrinsic value of the business (governance advantage), or (c) they must be able to match the business to a more synergistic corporate owner than is immediately available (timing advantage). We discuss why, and under what conditions, PE firms may thus have an advantage in buying, owning, and selling businesses, and derive a set of propositions predicting which targets PE firms are most likely to pursue. Our study thus offers a comprehensive yet contingent theory of non-venture PE, developing an integrated value-based framework to explain this important and growing phenomenon. In doing so, we also offer new insights into the role of intermediaries in strategic factor markets, especially the market for the buying and selling of businesses.
AB  - We examine the role of non-venture private equity (PE) firms as intermediaries in the market for corporate assets. We argue that, in order to create and capture value by acquiring established businesses and selling them to corporate buyers, PE firms must possess at least one of three potential advantages: (a) they must be able to identify businesses that are currently undervalued (valuation advantage), (b) they must be able to enhance the intrinsic value of the business (governance advantage), or (c) they must be able to match the business to a more synergistic corporate owner than is immediately available (timing advantage). We discuss why, and under what conditions, PE firms may thus have an advantage in buying, owning, and selling businesses, and derive a set of propositions predicting which targets PE firms are most likely to pursue. Our study thus offers a comprehensive yet contingent theory of non-venture PE, developing an integrated value-based framework to explain this important and growing phenomenon. In doing so, we also offer new insights into the role of intermediaries in strategic factor markets, especially the market for the buying and selling of businesses.
